// Regression: constructing an instance of a class *imported from another
// module* via the bare `ClassName(args)` form, then reading a field on it
// directly, now works -- previously the construction itself type-checked
// fine, but the resulting variable's type wasn't registered for a later
// raw field access ("Field access on non-class type 'Widget'"), even
// though calling a *method* on the same instance always worked.
// parser/type_system.py's FIELD_ACCESS handling deferred this error only
// for a composite generic type ("Tuple<int32, string>") not yet merged
// in; a plain imported class name ("Widget") needed the same deferral,
// since it's equally unresolved at the point this file's own (pre-merge)
// parse runs -- FIR conversion resolves the real field type afterward
// from the fully-merged class definitions, independent of this check.
//
// (classes_widget_helper.fire, the sibling module this test imports,
// exists solely to exercise this cross-module path.)
import @firescript/std.io.println;
import classes_widget_helper.Widget;

w: Widget = Widget(7);
println(w.val);

/* EXPECT
7
*/
